<DOC><DOCNO> AP880712-0023 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-88 0123EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r p PM-Convention-TV     07-12 0310</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Convention-TV,280</SECOND><HEAD>With PM-Convention-Networks Bjt</HEAD><HEAD>Networks Plan Prime-Time Convention Coverage</HEAD><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The three major networks plan to carry livecoverage of the Democratic National Convention for approximatelytwo hours of prime time each night, Monday through Thursday.   All three networks plan coverage from 9-11 p.m. EDT each night.CBS will start at 8 p.m. on Thursday.   ABC's coverage will be anchored by Peter Jennings withcommentary by David Brinkley. ``World News Tonight'' and ``GoodMorning America'' will originate from Atlanta during theconvention. ``Nightline'' will stay home in Washington, but willinclude reports on the convention as news merits.   Walter Cronkite, who is under contract negotiations with CBS,nevertheless returns for his 19th convention serving as networkcommentator. Dan Rather will anchor the convention coverage. ``CBSEvening News'' will originate from Atlanta, as will ``CBS ThisMorning.''   NBC's Tom Brokaw will anchor his network's coverage with JohnChancellor providing commentary. ``NBC Nightly News'' and the``Today'' show will originate from Atlanta.   C-SPAN will carry each session of the convention live withoutcommentary each night.   Cable News Network will have updates throughout the day, thencarry complete live coverage of the convention session each night,followed by a half-hour wrapup, then ``Crossfire'' and ``InsidePolitics '88.'' Convention highlights will be shown 4-6 a.m. EDT.   PBS' ``MacNeil-Lehrer NewsHour'' will also report from theconvention.   In the battle of the political columnist-commentators, ABClanded columnists George F. Will and Tom Wicker. CBS snagged KevinPhillips and Roger Rosenblatt.   CNN's lineup of experts include columnists Patrick Buchanan, TomBraden, Rowland Evans, Mark Green and Robert Novak. PBS has U.S.News andamp; World Report Editor David Gergen and Washington Postcolumnist Mark Shields.   NBC says it is depending on its own Chancellor, Brokaw andpolitical reporter Ken Bode, though political consultants BobSquier and John Sears will offer commentary on ``Today.''</TEXT></DOC>